{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568997"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:23:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:23:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21604"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21604"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.08,0.01,0.06,0.81]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14473"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103045"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14473"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21604"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85509"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12089"},{"type":"tags","id":"12090"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"36406"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43753"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103045"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns about brown patches that have developed on her face over the past two months. She is 24 weeks pregnant with her first child and is worried these might indicate a medical problem. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications apart from pregnancy vitamins. She works as a teacher and reports spending time outdoors during playground duty. She denies using any new skincare products.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are symmetrical light-brown patches on her forehead, cheeks, and upper lip. She also has a dark line running down the middle of her abdomen and some small red spider-like lesions on her upper chest.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management for the facial pigmentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical corticosteroids","Referral to dermatology","Oral antihistamines","Topical hydroquinone cream","Reassurance and sun protection"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with melasma, a common hyperpigmentation disorder affecting up to 70% of pregnant women. It typically appears as symmetrical light-brown patches on the face, particularly on the forehead, cheeks, and upper lip. The patient also demonstrates other normal physiological skin changes of pregnancy including linea nigra (the dark line on her abdomen) and spider naevi on her chest.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance and sun protection\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management for melasma during pregnancy. The patient should be informed that this is a common and benign condition related to hormonal changes of pregnancy. Sun exposure exacerbates melasma, so broad-spectrum sunscreen (SPF 30+), wide-brimmed hats, and sun avoidance are recommended. Most cases improve spontaneously after delivery, though some may persist.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical hydroquinone cream\u003C/strong\u003E is a depigmenting agent that can be effective for melasma, but it is not recommended during pregnancy due to concerns about systemic absorption and potential fetal effects. This treatment would be considered only after pregnancy and breastfeeding are complete if the melasma persists.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antihistamines\u003C/strong\u003E would not be effective for melasma as it is not an allergic or inflammatory condition. Antihistamines are used for pruritic conditions such as urticaria or allergic reactions, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical corticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated for melasma and may actually worsen the condition by causing skin atrophy and telangiectasia. They are used for inflammatory skin conditions, which melasma is not.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral to dermatology\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary for typical pregnancy-related melasma. Specialist referral would be considered if the diagnosis was uncertain, if there were unusual features, or if the condition persisted significantly after pregnancy and was causing psychological distress.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Melasma is a common hyperpigmentation disorder affecting up to 70% of pregnant women, typically appearing on the face in the second half of pregnancy.","Physiological skin changes in pregnancy include linea nigra, spider naevi, palmar erythema, and increased pigmentation of existing pigmented areas.","Telogen effluvium is a normal postpartum phenomenon occurring 4-20 weeks after delivery, with recovery typically within 6 months."],"references":["Nelson-Piercy C. Handbook of obstetric medicine. 6th ed. Boca Raton: CRC Press; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85509"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21604"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85509"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-19T05:18:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-19T05:19:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14473"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103045"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"73","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/73"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Post-graduate","synonyms":null,"description":"Not suitable for a medical student","position":2,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing,